of racketeering and fraud.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal prosecutors are considering reversingcourse and allowing Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to pay indictedfinancier Michael R. Milken more than $100 million for work he didlast year, sources say.   The provision barring Drexel from paying its former junk bondtrader his 1988 compensation was included in the investment firm'sformal settlement of criminal securities fraud charges brought bythe government.   The sources spoke Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Disappointing second-quarter salesprompted Eastman Kodak Co. to announce a reorganization that willtrim 4,500 jobs from its worldwide payroll this year.   The photo company on Wednesday acknowledged the cuts were 3,500jobs above what was previously forecast. Kodak employs 145,000people worldwide.   Kodak will also restructure or divest businesses with annualrevenues of $1.25 billion through sale, closure or reorganization,the company said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A task force within Digital Equipment Corp. hasissued a memo urging at least nine of the computer maker'sdepartments to cut their work forces by 25 percent through attritionor transfer by July 1991.   Only an estimated 30,000 of the Maynard-based company's 125,800employees would be affected by the memo, putting the total reductionin employees at about 7,500, analysts said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wang Laboratories Inc. has named as president a48-year-old executive who helped build the new Penn Central Corp.and competed with the Japanese in consumer electronics.   Richard Miller was portrayed by Wang on Wednesday as a turnaroundspecialist who could help the Lowell, Mass.-based minicomputercompany recover from last year's $424 million loss and the defectionof some nervous customers.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Malcolm Forbes said he has no intention of tryingto make U.S. taxpayers foot the bill for his $2 million birthdaybash in Morocco _ even though he thinks he could.   Forbes held a news conference Wednesday to deflect criticism thatfollowed speculation he might try to deduct some party costs fromhis taxes. He said he would not seek a business expense deductioneven though a case could be made for one.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices ran up a broad gain Wednesday. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 27.12 points to 2,678.11.   Bond prices rose sharply after what analysts called a strongmarket response to the government auction of 5-year Treasury notes.   The dollar regained some of its sharp losses from earlier in theweek in thin, volatile trading.   Copper futures prices rallied strongly on New York's CommodityExchange. Most oil futures advanced, while grains and soybeans weremostly lower.</TEXT></DOC>